 The major outcomes of this project are

Provided enabling methods to measure, compress, and analyze streaming Big Data that are otherwise very challenging to handle due to their complex structure and high volume;
Bridged the gap between quality control research, which fails to address challenges posed by Big Data, and statistical learning research, which ignores quality improvement principles and objectives;  
Proposed new statistical and machine learning methods for analysis of mutlistream high-dimensional data for the purpose of online anomaly detection.
Created new methodologies Enabling process monitoring and the diagnosis of advanced manufacturing systems to improve the system performance and quality of products;
Integrated new computational algorithms with statistical modeling techniques to create an efficient and scalable analytical methodology for real-time analysis of Big Data;
Proposed methodologies for adaptive and compressive sampling to speed up the inspection in advanced manufacturing systems and help with their scale-up;
The developed methodologies were validated using real data from various advanced manufacturing systems.
The outcome of the project generated multiple publications in  high-quality journal such as Technometrics, Structural Health Monitoring, etc. as well as conference presentations to the academic communities and to industrial collaborators. The journal articles and conference presentation slides will also be posted on the PI?s website to distribute the research results and exchange ideas. The methods proposed in this proposal were coded and delivered via Matlab and R packages that enables fast computation and implementation of these methods for streaming Big Data. 


